In article &lt;8711170236.AA01150@speed.sun.com&gt; nowicki@SUN.COM (Bill Nowicki) writes:
&gt;For example, if I send mail to user@Apple.COM it does an MX lookup and
&gt;sends it via Relay.CS.NET near Boston, and then waits until Apple polls
&gt;the relay via a long-distance call.  Ideally it would instead be
&gt;delivered through our direct UUCP link, since they are only a local
&gt;call away from us.  I think Horton, Partidge et al who devised the MX
&gt;record scheme (RFCs 974 and 976) had thought about doing something
&gt;like the UUCP "pathalias" package, but opted for the simpler solution
&gt;instead.

You obviously have to keep the information that you have a
non-Internet route to Apple.Com somewhere.  If you want to always try
the Internet first, you could probably get your site listed as a
("high-cost"?) MX forwarder to Apple.Com and have your software
recognise that if it is one of the MX forwarders it should look for a
non-Internet route to the site.  Of course you should be willing and
able to route some mail if you advertise you site as an MX forwarder. 

(My understanding of such things may be wrong, I havn't read the RFC's
carefully.  It may be a violation of one of them to use the "High-Cost"
forwarder (your own host) rather than the "Low-Cost" one.  You
obviously should only use this solution to sites you have a reliable
non-internet connection to.)
